I've always loved history. Both my parents being professors of it probably played a role, but now that I'm my own person I still study it as a hobby. It really teaches lessons - too bad most people ignore them. Also, I find stories of real people, their lives and their world more interesting and engaging than fiction.

There is also an element of nostalgia, of sorts, to learning about the past. So much has been lost: the stories of people's lives, the very ways in which they perceived the world, their art, their lore... It feels good to make a connection to those who came before by studying what they left behind, but there is always the accompanying sadness of realizing some things we will never know. This is really the only sort of romanticism not alien to me. This nostalgic element is probably the reason I find ancient history most interesting - it's the most unknowable.

